# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-payment-conspiracy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] The **10 agorot controversy** refers to a conspiracy theory made public by Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat's appearance at a specially convened session of the UN Security Council in Geneva on 25 May 1990.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] At the session, Arafat claimed that the obverse design of an Israeli ten agorot coin showed a map of "Greater Israel" that represented Zionist expansionist goals.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] In support of his claim that the 10 agorot coins displayed a Greater Israel, Arafat also quoted a 1989 paper by Gwyn Rowley of the University of Sheffield published in *GeoJournal*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] The paper titled "Developing Perspectives upon the Areal Extent of Israel: An Outline Evaluation" raised the question of what the maximum territorial extents of Eretz Yisrael were in the eyes of Israelis.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] As part of this inquiry, Rowley presented a map of the Middle East with a superimposed outline based on the embossed pattern of a contemporary 10 agorot coin.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] Berkowicz, of the Department of Physical Geography, at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem criticized Rowley's article in a subsequent paper also published by *GeoJournal*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] Berkowicz concluded that the shape was based on an ancient coin and "There is of course no foundation to Rowley's undocumented claim." Rowley then responded that the coin might have been chosen because of its map-like shape.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] Arafat's meeting in Geneva generated widespread global media coverage.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] The Bank of Israel maintains that the 10 agorot design was selected for its historical value, and is a "replica of a coin issued by Mattathias Antigonus (40–37 B.C.E.) with the seven-branched candelabrum".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] The design, by Nathan Karp, first appeared on the 100 shekel coin issued by the Bank of Israel on 2 May 1984.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] When the old shekel currency was replaced by the new shekel in September 1985, the design was copied to the new 10 agorot coin, which was equal in value to the old 100 shekel.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/10-agorot-controversy] This design was also adopted as the symbol of the Bank of Israel.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The **lepers' plot** was an alleged conspiracy of French lepers in 1321 to spread their disease by contaminating water supplies, including well water, with their powders and poisons.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] According to the American historian Solomon Grayzel, lepers were the most abused group of people during the Middle Ages: they were thrown out of settlements and treated as wild animals due to the widespread belief that their disease was highly contagious.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] However, other historians have contested such a view, pointing out that lepers often lived within communities in leper houses (*leprosaria*) and were supported by charitable donations.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] As the alleged conspiracy progressed, Jews and Muslims were also said to be implicated, providing an excuse for local authorities to attack both Jewish and leper communities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The hysteria quickly spread to the neighbouring realms, most notably to the Crown of Aragon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Rumours of a plot broke out in the spring of 1321 and terrified the people of southern France.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Torture of lepers ensued, and eventually, confessions were forced out.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] These initially blamed lepers only, but later, in June 1321, stated that the lepers were acting on the orders of Jews, who in turn had been bribed by the Muslims of Spain, in an attempt to "poison the Christian population of Europe".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The records of Jacques Fournier, Bishop of Pamiers (who will later be elected as Pope Benedict XII), contain the 9 June 1321 deposition of Guillaume Agasse, the head of the leper house in Pamiers.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Agasse said that "50 or 60" representatives, leaders, and ministers of leper houses from across France met in one place and conspired to poison the populace with the aid of the Muslim King of Granada.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The heads of the houses, it was claimed, were required to deny 'Christ's faith and his law' and in return were to become the masters of the localities their houses served.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The alleged plot flourished in the wake of the previous year's Shepherds' Crusade, which saw young rural men and women form a mob and attack Jews in France and the neighbouring Crown of Aragon, despite being ordered to stop by Pope John XXII, King Philip V of France and King James II of Aragon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The rumours that sparked the violence in 1321 may have started here.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] While the Shepherds' Crusade was led by rioters, the persecution of lepers was orchestrated by municipal authorities, making it judicial though extralegal (judicial power being royal prerogative).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] King Philip was on a regional tour when the stories started circulating.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] He found himself in a difficult position‍—‍he could openly neither condone nor condemn the unstoppable persecution, as the former would have led to more violence, while the latter would have undermined his authority.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The Dominican inquisitor Bernard Gui was instructed to conduct extensive investigation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] On 21 June, Philip ordered by edict that all lepers be imprisoned and examined under torture.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Those found guilty were to be burnt at the stake.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Since their crimes were declared lèse-majesté, the lepers' property was to be confiscated by the Crown.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Unfortunately for Philip, many local lords had already executed lepers and confiscated their goods.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] He was persuaded by the barons, prelates, and nobles, who said they had by ancient custom the right to administer leproseries and take immediate steps against the plotters, to give way and accept their actions through a second ordinance on August 18.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] News of the uncovered plot spread rapidly to the neighbouring countries.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] King James of Aragon learned of the supposed conspiracy and associated violence almost immediately.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] James's cousin, King Sancho of Majorca, informed him of the situation in France by a letter dated 2 June, but James deliberated for nearly a week.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The French lepers fleeing the "lash of justice", as James put it in a letter to his officials, were already seeking shelter in his realm.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] He cautiously commanded the arrest and expulsion of all leprous foreigners, while Jews were not mentioned.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] By 27 June, James had changed his mind in favour of a harsher approach.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] He ordered not only the seizure of the diseased, destruction of their powders, and questioning under torture, but also the arrest and expulsion of non-leprous foreigners, "since it is difficult, truly even impossible, to recognize such and identify them".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Local inquisitions were set up in Manresa, Ejea de los Caballeros, Huesca, Montblanc, Tarazona and Barcelona.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Leper colonies were attacked and their goods seized, including the ancient leprosarium attached to the church of Santa Maria de Cervera.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] A suspected leper was most likely examined and diagnosed with the disease by frightened lay people rather than experienced physicians.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] A year after the scare, a physician called Amonant decided to move from Gascony to Aragon, only to be apprehended in Huesca and accused of being a leper intending to poison the water.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The physician appealed to King James's son Alfons and was granted examination by local physicians, who confirmed that he was not infected.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The incident was probably one of many that helped promote the medical diagnosis of leprosy.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Doubts about whether the lepers' plot was real or not emerged soon after the persecution of lepers in France in June, July, and August 1321.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Those lepers of Limoges who were branded and locked up on 27 August in response to the royal edict were released only a month later, despite the original intention that confinement should be permanent.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The original accusations were already being questioned.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] Jews continued to be persecuted, but references to poisoning of the water supply by lepers were progressively treated with more scepticism, and the phrase 'it is said that' appears more often in official records.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] In 1338, Pope Benedict XII issued a Bull in response to pleas from the lepers of Toulouse for support in recovering goods, including property and lands, confiscated during the plot.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The Pope said that the lepers had already been recognised in court as 'innocent and guiltless' of the crimes of which they had been accused and were therefore due formal restitution.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1321-lepers-plot] The Pope was the same Jacques Fournier who twenty years before had been one of the interrogators of Agassa.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The **Great Kantō Earthquake** (Japanese: 関東大地震, *Kantō daijishin*, or 関東大震災, *Kantō daishinsai*) was a megathrust earthquake that struck the Kantō Plain on the main Japanese island of Honshu at 11:58:32 JST (02:58:32 UTC) on Saturday, 1 September 1923.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It had an approximate magnitude of 8.0 on the moment magnitude scale (Mw), with its epicenter located some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of the capital Tokyo.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake devastated Tokyo, the port city of Yokohama, and the surrounding prefectures of Kanagawa, Chiba, and Shizuoka, causing widespread damage throughout the Kantō region.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The event was a complex disaster, with modern research indicating it consisted of three consecutive shocks in the span of several minutes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial megathrust event in Kanagawa Prefecture was followed three minutes later by a magnitude 7.2 earthquake centered beneath Tokyo Bay, and two minutes after that by a magnitude 7.3 shock in Yamanashi Prefecture.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires, exacerbated by strong winds from a nearby typhoon, spread rapidly through the densely populated urban areas, accounting for the majority of the devastation and casualties.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The death toll is estimated to have been between 105,000 and 140,000 people, including tens of thousands who went missing and were presumed dead.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over half of Tokyo and nearly all of Yokohama were destroyed, leaving approximately 2.5 million people homeless.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster triggered widespread social unrest, including the Kantō Massacre, in which ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them were murdered by vigilante groups based on false rumors.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the aftermath, the Japanese government declared martial law and undertook extensive relief and restoration efforts.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake prompted ambitious plans for the reconstruction of Tokyo, aiming to create a modern, resilient imperial capital under the leadership of Home Minister Gotō Shinpei.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, these plans were often met with political contestation, financial constraints, and local resistance, leading to a reconstruction that, while significantly improving infrastructure, fell short of the grandest visions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also fueled debates about national identity, modernity, and societal values, with many commentators interpreting the event as a divine punishment for perceived moral decline and advocating for spiritual and social regeneration.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake remains a pivotal event in modern Japanese history, profoundly impacting urban planning, disaster preparedness, and social consciousness.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September is commemorated annually in Japan as Disaster Prevention Day.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Kantō region of eastern Japan is prone to major earthquakes due to its location near complex tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The 1923 earthquake occurred when the Philippine Sea Plate subducted beneath the Okhotsk Plate (sometimes considered part of the North American Plate) along the Sagami Trough.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial shock, occurring at 11:58:32 JST on 1 September 1923, was a complex event.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Modern analysis indicates a dual rupture on a broad trench-type fault: the first rupture occurred near Odawara in Kanagawa Prefecture, some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of Tokyo, followed about ten seconds later by a second shock on the other side of Sagami Bay near the Miura Peninsula.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was followed minutes later by two major aftershocks: a magnitude 7.2 earthquake beneath northern Tokyo Bay at 12:01, and a magnitude 7.3 earthquake in Yamanashi Prefecture at 12:03.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts consistently describe these three distinct seismic events.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake immediately toppled structures, crushed people, and caused widespread panic.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts describe an initial period of stunned silence followed by a frantic rush as people tried to reunite with family and salvage belongings.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Mononobe Nagao recalled the earth shaking "back and forth for what seemed like 15 seconds", followed by violent vertical convulsions that knocked people to the ground.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Writer Tanaka Kōtarō described the sound as akin to a giant "blackening whirlwind" churning up the earth from "deep underground".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Within thirty minutes of the first tremor, more than 130 major fires broke out across Tokyo, particularly in the densely populated eastern and northeastern sections.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These fires were fueled by overturned charcoal braziers used for midday meals, leaking gas from ruptured lines, and flammable debris from collapsed wooden buildings.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Strong winds, associated with a typhoon passing off the coast, fanned the flames, creating massive firestorms that swept through the city.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The air temperature in some areas reached 46 °C (115 °F).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The combination of ongoing aftershocks and rapidly spreading fires led to pandemonium.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Millions of residents attempted to flee, often carrying their possessions, which clogged the already damaged streets and bridges.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kawatake Shigetoshi described being trapped in a "wave of people" in eastern Tokyo, unable to move as fires approached from multiple directions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many sought refuge in open spaces, such as parks and the grounds surrounding the Imperial Palace, but these areas quickly became overcrowded.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Waterways like the Sumida River also became congested with boats as people tried to escape by water, only to face sparks and burning debris falling from the sky.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster quickly overwhelmed Tokyo's infrastructure and its capacity for an orderly evacuation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake was one of the most destructive natural disasters of the 20th century.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly half of Tokyo and virtually all of Yokohama were transformed into "blackened, corpse-strewn wastelands".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and subsequent fires destroyed an estimated 397,119 homes in Tokyo Prefecture alone, leaving about 1.38 million people homeless in Tokyo City.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Across the seven affected prefectures (Tokyo, Kanagawa, Chiba, Saitama, Shizuoka, Yamanashi, and Ibaraki), a total of 2.5 million people were displaced.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In addition to buildings, the earthquake buckled roads, collapsed bridges (362 destroyed and 70 heavily damaged in Tokyo), twisted train tracks, snapped water and sewer pipes, and severed telegraph lines.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main aqueduct from Wadabori collapsed in two places and required extensive repairs.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The sea floor in Sagami Bay dropped by over 400 meters (1,300 ft) at the epicenter, triggering tsunamis that inundated low-lying coastal communities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires were the primary cause of destruction, accounting for 90 percent of the fatalities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, districts like Asakusa, Kanda, Nihonbashi, Kyōbashi, Honjo, and Fukagawa were largely incinerated.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Honjo Clothing Depot, a large open area where tens of thousands sought refuge, became a death trap when a massive firestorm (a *tatsumaki* or whirlwind of fire) engulfed it, killing an estimated 40,000 people in minutes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor Koizumi Tomi described the site as "hell on earth", surrounded by "endless rows of bodies: red, inflamed bodies; black, swollen bodies; bodies partially buried under ash and smoldering remains".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government administration was crippled.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, 44 percent of the main buildings burned to the ground, including the police headquarters and the ministries of Home Affairs, Finance, Education, Communications, and Railways.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The vast majority of police stations and municipal and ward offices crumbled or burned.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Out of Tokyo's 196 primary schools, 117 were destroyed, along with numerous higher girls' schools, trade schools, colleges, and universities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, including public dining halls, cheap lodging homes, and crèches, were annihilated.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over 160 public and private hospitals in Tokyo were destroyed.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster exacerbated the economic downturn of the early 1920s and contributed to a genuine banking crisis in 1927.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 7,000 factories were destroyed, including major spinning, dyeing, and tool manufacturing plants.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Financial institutions suffered heavily, with 121 of 138 bank head offices and 222 of 310 branch offices in Tokyo City consumed by fire or reduced to rubble.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Insurance policies offered little relief, as most contained clauses exempting companies from earthquake-related damage; eventually, the government intervened to facilitate partial payouts.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Reconstruction brought a new surge of imports and, under these combined pressures, an early return to the gold standard was impossible.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also led to significant unemployment.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In September 1923, the unemployment rate in the wards of Tokyo reached 45% (59% for men, 28% for women).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 15 November, across Tokyo Prefecture, 178,887 people were registered as unemployed, with the commerce and industry sectors most affected.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The human toll of the Great Kantō Earthquake was catastrophic.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Early estimates put the death toll as high as 140,000, but modern research based on the *1923 Great Kantō Earthquake Disaster Report* puts the total number of fatalities at 105,385.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Of these, 91,781 deaths (87%) were attributed to fires, while 11,086 (10.5%) were due to being crushed by collapsing buildings.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Other causes included drowning and landslides.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kanagawa Prefecture suffered 32,838 deaths, while Tokyo Prefecture had 70,387.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An additional 13,275 people remained classified as missing twelve months after the earthquake.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] People died in numerous ways: crushed by collapsing buildings, trampled in panicked crowds, burned alive in the fires, or drowned in rivers and canals while attempting to escape the flames.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some victims suffocated as fires consumed oxygen, while others were boiled alive in ponds offering no protection from the intense heat.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The smell of burning human flesh and decaying bodies permeated the air for weeks.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Disposing of the dead became a major public health concern, leading to mass cremations, particularly at the Honjo Clothing Depot.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the immediate aftermath of the earthquake, law and order broke down in many parts of the affected region.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This period was characterized by the spread of rumors, the formation of vigilante groups (*jikeidan*), and the massacre of ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them, as well as the murder of political activists by the authorities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Widespread destruction of communication infrastructure contributed to an atmosphere of uncertainty and fear.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Rumors spread rapidly, often relayed by refugees fleeing the disaster zone.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some stories suggested that Mount Fuji had erupted or that a large tsunami had washed away Yokohama.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most damaging rumors, however, concerned alleged activities by Koreans.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Originating from looting by Japanese in Yokohama that was misattributed to Koreans, false reports circulated that Koreans were poisoning wells, committing arson, looting, and organizing attacks on Japanese.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These rumors were given a degree of legitimacy when some government officials, including Gotō Fumio of the Home Ministry, broadcast messages warning of "organized groups of Korean extremists" attempting to "commit acts of sedition".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 2 September, the police headquarters, lacking manpower to confirm eyewitness reports, passed them on as factual and issued a statement that "unscrupulous Koreans are committing acts of arson and other forms of violence".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fueled by these rumors and a climate of fear and xenophobia, Japanese vigilante groups, known as *jikeidan*, formed across the Kantō region.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By mid-September, an estimated 3,689 such groups were operating, ostensibly to prevent fires, stop looting, and maintain order.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of these groups, often armed with makeshift weapons like clubs, swords, and bamboo spears, targeted Koreans and, in some cases, Chinese, Okinawans, and Japanese from certain regions who were mistaken for Koreans due to their accents.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Estimates of the death toll in what became known as the Kantō Massacre vary significantly.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Police confirmed the deaths of 248 Koreans, while an investigation by the Governor-General of Korea determined 832 had been killed or were missing.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A separate investigation by Korean students concluded that 2,613 Koreans had been killed; some modern estimates reach as high as 6,000.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Victims were often subjected to brutal violence, including beatings, stabbings, and lynchings, sometimes after being "tested" for their Korean identity (e.g., by being asked to pronounce Japanese words that were difficult for Koreans).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While some police and military personnel attempted to protect Koreans, others were complicit in the violence or turned a blind eye.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Although police made belated corrections to the rumors on 3 and 4 September, few perpetrators were prosecuted; of 125 vigilante group members tried, only 32 received formal sentences, and 91 received suspended sentences.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Contemporary commentators like Hoashi Ri'ichirō and Oku Hidesaburō condemned the massacres as "extremely disgusting and internationally shameful" and a "disgraceful act that exposed a moral flaw".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The chaos also provided a cover for the murder of political dissidents.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most prominent case was the Amakasu Incident, in which the anarchist Sakae Ōsugi, his partner Noe Itō, and his six-year-old nephew were arrested and then brutally killed by a squad of military police led by Lieutenant Masahiko Amakasu.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake struck at a time of political uncertainty in Japan.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Prime Minister Katō Tomosaburō had died on 24 August, and Admiral Yamamoto Gonnohyōe, selected to form a new cabinet, had not yet succeeded when the disaster occurred.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also forced the postponement of Crown Prince Hirohito's marriage and accession ceremonies.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This elite-level political vacuum contributed to confusion over who had the authority to deploy police and military personnel.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] General Ishimitsu Maomi, deputy commander of the Imperial Guard Forces, acted first, deploying troops to protect imperial locations.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Akaike Atsushi, inspector general of the Tokyo Metropolitan Police, faced an overwhelming task with outnumbered and unprepared forces.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The new cabinet was formally appointed on the afternoon of 2 September, sworn in on the lawn of the Akasaka Detached Palace amid falling ash, as other ministerial buildings were deemed unsafe.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] One of the first decisions of the new cabinet was to declare martial law over what remained of the capital on 2 September.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This ushered in the largest peacetime domestic mobilization and deployment of the army in Japan's pre–World War II history, with eventually over 52,000 troops deployed to Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The martial law headquarters was granted extensive powers, including administering relief and public safety, prosecuting lawbreakers, prohibiting public gatherings, censoring information, stopping and searching individuals, and entering private homes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Martial law remained in effect until 15 November.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Initial military deployment was fraught with difficulties.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Commanders arriving in Tokyo found a near total absence of reliable information and lines of communication were non-existent.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military had to rely on aerial reconnaissance and around 2,000 army-trained carrier pigeons for communication.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The zone of martial law was progressively expanded to cover all of Tokyo and Kanagawa Prefectures by 3 September, and Chiba and Saitama Prefectures by 4 September.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] To counter rumors and vigilante violence, particularly against Koreans, military authorities were empowered to arrest individuals, disband suspicious groups, and confiscate weapons.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] From 4 September, military and police began to collect and transport Koreans to government-run detention centers for "protective custody"; by the end of September, 23,715 Koreans had been taken into these centers.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Yamamoto cabinet created the Emergency Earthquake Relief Bureau (*Rinji shinsai kyūgo jimukyoku*) to oversee all relief and recovery efforts.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Providing emergency medical assistance was an immediate priority, but initial efforts were largely unsuccessful.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many organized rescue and first aid squads were unable to reach the worst-hit areas like Honjo, Asakusa, and Kanda until 4 or 5 September due to destroyed infrastructure and unofficial checkpoints by vigilante groups.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A dearth of medical supplies, due to the destruction of numerous hospitals and dispensaries, further hampered efforts.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau concentrated its limited medical resources at large open areas like Hibiya Park and Ueno Park, where tens of thousands of refugees had congregated.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over the longer term, mobile clinics and dispensaries proved most effective.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau created 41 units, and other organizations like Tokyo Prefecture, the Japan Red Cross Society, and the Mitsubishi Corporation also operated mobile clinics.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 30 November, these public and private clinics had provided care to 447,111 sufferers.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Temporary hospitals, some in tents donated by American and French governments, accommodated over 6,000 seriously wounded people.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Securing food and water was a critical challenge.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Mayor Hidejirō Nagata learned on 2 September that the army's main supply depot in Fukagawa, holding 8,000 *koku* of rice (enough to feed over 500,000 people for six days), had been completely destroyed by fire.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military managed to amass over 120,000 combat rations and 60,000 rations of rice from other stores.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 4 September, military units were distributing dried noodles.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Eventually, 74,048 *koku* of rice were transported from military installations across Japan to distribution centers in Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government also appealed to prefectural governors for rice donations, receiving pledges of 61,490 *koku* in the first week.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An "Emergency Requisition Ordinance" allowed the government to requisition foodstuffs and other materials.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Transporting these supplies was a major logistical challenge due to damaged rail lines and docks.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Navy personnel spent a week repairing 86 piers at Shibaura and Ryōgoku, while army forces cleared railway lines and rebuilt track.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Conservative estimates suggest that 1.25 million people received rice distributions between 6 and 10 September.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Water supply was an even more significant problem.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main water plant was not heavily damaged, but pipes and aquifers were severed in over two hundred locations.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Warships tanked water from Yokosuka, Osaka, and Nagoya, and the army requisitioned water barrels to transport clean water.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the end of December, nearly 40 million gallons (151 million liters) of drinking water had been transported.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Shelter options were bleak for Tokyo Prefecture's 1.55 million homeless.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Nearly 800,000 people left Tokyo or Yokohama, first on foot and later via restricted rail service (from 11 September), to stay with relatives or friends elsewhere.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] About 250,000 people dispersed to other parts of Japan, including 17,704 to Kobe, 7,600 to Hokkaidō, and some even to Japan's colonies like Taiwan and Karafuto.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Those remaining in Tokyo flooded large open spaces such as Hibiya Park, Ueno Park, and the Imperial Palace grounds.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 9 September, municipal authorities began constructing temporary barracks.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Meiji Shrine site housed nearly 6,000 refugees, Ueno Park over 9,500, and Hibiya Park 7,000.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of these open spaces became shantytowns.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Barracks were often cramped, with an average of 0.6 *tsubo* (about 2 square meters (22 sq ft)) of floor space per person.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Sanitation was a major problem, with makeshift latrines overflowing.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While a modest number of refugees left barrack housing by the end of 1923, many more returned to the disaster zone and erected private makeshift shacks.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By October 1923, 539,450 people were living in 111,791 such temporary abodes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government officials and media outlets made concerted efforts to construct the Great Kantō Earthquake as an unprecedented national calamity, requiring a unified national response.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Newspapers, the chief medium for disseminating news, played a lead role.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Major papers like the *Tokyo Nichi Nichi Shinbun*, *Osaka Asahi Shinbun*, and *Osaka Mainichi Shinbun* used emotive headlines, harrowing survivor accounts, vivid photographs, and even documentary motion pictures to convey the disaster's horror and scale to a national audience.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These portrayals often framed the disaster in terms of wartime analogies, emphasizing themes of sacrifice and national unity.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The forty-ninth-day memorial service held on 19 October 1923, at the site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, attended by over 200,000 people and leading politicians, was a meticulously choreographed event.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Speeches by figures like Gizō Kasuya and Shōzaburō Horie explicitly linked the victims' sacrifices to the future reconstruction of Tokyo and Japan, urging national unity and effort.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Visual culture, including lithographic prints and postcards, also played a significant role in disseminating the image of a devastated but resilient capital, and of a concerned government responding to the crisis.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Postcards depicting dead bodies, while sometimes classified as contraband, were widespread and brought the human cost of the disaster to a national audience in a stark manner.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A widespread interpretation, embraced by numerous elites across various sectors of society, was that the earthquake was an act of divine punishment (*tenken* or *tenbatsu*) or heavenly warning.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This view was not confined to religious leaders but was articulated by bureaucrats, politicians, academics, and social commentators.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster was seen as a response to Japan's perceived moral decline, materialism, luxury-mindedness, hedonism, and excessive individualism that had become prominent since World War I.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The entertainment districts of Tokyo, such as Asakusa, and centers of consumer spending, like the Ginza, were often singled out as epicenters of this perceived degeneracy and thus seen as specifically targeted by the heavens.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The destruction of icons of modern consumerism, such as the Mitsukoshi Department Store and the twelve-story Ryōunkaku tower in Asakusa, was imbued with symbolic meaning.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This interpretation served as a cosmological bolster for critiques of contemporary society and legitimated calls for social, moral, and ideological reform.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake was thus framed as a moral wake-up call, placing Japan at a crossroads between decline and renovation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The interpretation of the earthquake as divine admonishment fueled calls for national spiritual renewal (*seishin fukkō*) and economic moderation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An Imperial Rescript Regarding the Invigoration of the National Spirit, issued on 10 November 1923, became a foundational document for this movement.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It urged Japanese people to reject frivolousness, extravagance, and extreme tendencies, and to embrace simplicity, sincerity, fortitude, diligence, thrift, moderation, loyalty, and filial piety.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government campaigns, such as the 1924 Campaign for the Encouragement of Diligence and Thrift (*Kinken shōrei undō*), employed the memory of the earthquake to promote austerity and national savings.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Policies like the 1924 luxury tariff, which placed a 100 percent duty on a wide range of imported goods deemed luxuries, aimed to curb consumer spending and foster economic self-discipline.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While these measures had mixed results in altering consumer behavior in the long term, they reflected a broader elite concern with reorienting Japanese society towards more traditional and disciplined values.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The push for spiritual renewal also involved using schools, neighborhood associations, and new media like film and radio to inculcate desired moral values.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The devastation of Tokyo unleashed a wave of optimism among many bureaucrats, urban planners, and social reformers, who saw an unparalleled opportunity to rebuild the city as a modern, rational, and resilient metropolis.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Figures like Gotō Shinpei, Abe Isoo, and Fukuda Tokuzō argued that "old Tokyo" had been a breeding ground for social ills due to overcrowding, poor sanitation, poverty, and inadequate infrastructure.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake, they believed, created a chance to rectify these problems and construct a capital that would reflect new social values and assist the state in managing its subjects.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction offered a "free field" for new ideas, but reconstruction under Gotō's direction was swift.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many visions for the new Tokyo were influenced by "authoritarian high modernism," emphasizing state-led planning, technical and scientific progress, and intervention in many aspects of human life, from public health and housing to urban layout and transportation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans called for wider, paved streets, extensive green belts and parks, modern public housing, new sanitation systems, and improved transportation networks.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some, like Gotō Shinpei, envisioned a grand imperial capital that would project Japan's emerging power and prestige on the international stage, hoping to create a city that matched Paris and Berlin.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the initial optimism, reconstruction planning was fraught with political contestation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō Shinpei, as Home Minister and head of the Reconstruction Institute (*Teito fukkōin*), championed ambitious and expensive plans, initially proposing a budget of ¥3 billion—more than twice the entire national budget at the time.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was met with immediate opposition from Finance Minister Inoue Junnosuke and other cabinet colleagues, who were concerned about the nation's financial stability and favored a more fiscally conservative approach.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Debates raged over the scope of reconstruction, the extent of land readjustment, the design of new infrastructure, and, crucially, the budget.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Imperial Capital Reconstruction Deliberative Council (*Teito fukkō shingikai*), an advisory body of elder statesmen and party leaders, became the site of fierce opposition.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Critics, led by Itō Miyoji, argued the plans were extravagant, could lead to financial collapse, and violated constitutional rights to ownership.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The political infighting exposed deep divisions within Japan's elite and the structural weaknesses of its quasi-democratic, bureaucratic-oligarchic political system.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō's plans were progressively scaled back, with the budget reduced to ¥597 million by the council and further to ¥468 million by the Diet in December 1923.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A key component of the physical reconstruction was land readjustment (*kukaku seiri*).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Special Urban Planning Law of December 1923 empowered the government to rationalize irregular land plots, widen streets, and create public spaces by confiscating up to 10 percent of private land without monetary compensation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 30,000,000 square meters (320,000,000 sq ft) of land in Tokyo were divided into 66 readjustment districts.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While the process aimed to create a more rational and user-friendly urban environment, it was met with confusion, resistance, and numerous petitions from landowners and tenants.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Concerns involved the constitutionality of uncompensated land confiscation, the impact on businesses, the rights of tenants, and the adequacy of compensation for relocated structures.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite these local-level disputes, the program resulted in the rationalization of many neighborhoods, particularly in eastern Tokyo, and the creation of significant new public land for roads and other infrastructure.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Overall, about 15.3 percent of residential land in readjustment areas was converted to public use, with landowners compensated for acquisitions beyond the 10 percent threshold.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the time reconstruction was officially celebrated in March 1930, Tokyo had undergone significant physical changes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most notable successes were in transportation infrastructure.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The total area of roads in Tokyo increased by 45 percent, and many were widened and paved, with modern sidewalks.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Key arterial roads like Shōwa-dōri and Yasukuni-dōri were constructed, and new, modern steel bridges, such as the Eitai-bashi and Kiyosu-bashi spanning the Sumida River, became icons of the new city.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The river and canal system was also improved.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of the more ambitious social and environmental goals were not fully realized.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Spending on parks and green spaces, while resulting in three new large parks and 52 smaller ones, was limited.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, while improved, also received a small fraction of the reconstruction budget.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of the pre-earthquake urban vulnerabilities and social problems, including slum areas, persisted or re-emerged.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The final reconstruction expenditure by national and city governments totaled roughly ¥744 million.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, where tens of thousands perished, became a focal point for mourning and remembrance.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans for a memorial were initiated soon after the disaster.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In June 1924, the Taishō Earthquake Disaster Memorial Project Association was formed to oversee the project.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A national design competition for the memorial complex was launched in December 1924.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The winning entry by engineer-architect Maeda Kenjirō, a 53-meter (174 ft) tower, proved controversial due to its perceived resemblance to a Prussian triumphal tower and its perceived insensitivity to Buddhist sensibilities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] After sustained protest, particularly from Buddhist federations, the design was scrapped in December 1926.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Itō Chūta was then appointed to create a new, more "Japanese" design, heavily influenced by Buddhist architecture, featuring a pagoda that would house a charnel house.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Earthquake Memorial Hall (later the Tokyo Metropolitan Memorial Hall) in Yokoamichō Park was completed on 1 September 1930.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake left an indelible mark on Japan.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September was designated as Disaster Prevention Day (防災の日, *Bōsai no hi*) in 1960, an annual commemoration involving nationwide disaster drills and awareness campaigns.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster highlighted urban vulnerabilities and influenced subsequent approaches to city planning and building codes, although the ideal of a truly disaster-proof city remained elusive.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The memory of the earthquake, particularly the firestorms and the Honjo Clothing Depot tragedy, continued to haunt Tokyoites, influencing their behavior even during the World War II bombings.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The events of 1923 also served as a catalyst for long-term government efforts to foster neighborhood associations (*tonarigumi*) and promote civil defense, trends that intensified in the 1930s and during the war.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction caused by the disaster marked a "significant divide" in the "massification" of culture, consumption, and taste, accelerating social and cultural changes and providing a "free field" for new artistic and radical movements.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The center of urban life in Tokyo also shifted, as the old merchant quarters of the *shitamachi* ("Low City") were particularly devastated, pushing development toward the more residential "High City" (*yamanote*).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the significant scaling-back of Gotō Shinpei's original vision, the reconstruction provided a fine example of creative recovery, rebuilding Tokyo as a modern city and serving as a model for urban development throughout Japan until the end of World War II.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and its aftermath remain a subject of historical study and public memory, serving as a stark reminder of Japan's seismic activity and the complex interplay of disaster, society, and national identity.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The **1951 Pont-Saint-Esprit mass poisoning**, known in French as **Le Pain Maudit**, took place on 15 August 1951, in the small town of Pont-Saint-Esprit in Southern France.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] More than 250 people were involved, including 50 people interned in asylums, and there were seven deaths.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] A foodborne illness was suspected; among these it was originally believed to be a case of "cursed bread" (*pain maudit*).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] A majority of academic sources accept naturally occurring ergot poisoning as the cause of the epidemic, while a few theorise other causes such as poisoning by mercury, mycotoxins, or nitrogen trichloride.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] During the Vichy government, the supply of grains from field to mill to bakery was directed by the government's grain control board, the Office National Interprofessionnel des Céréales (ONIC), and later the Union Meunière.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Essentially, this created a government monopoly on the sale of flour, allowing the government a measure of control over wartime supply shortages.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] This also meant that flour would be purchased directly from ONIC, and delivered to the baker for a set price, without the baker having any control on quality.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Following the end of the second world war, this system was relaxed, allowing for bakers to have some choice over their flour supply.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] ONIC retained its monopoly on inter-departmental exportation and importation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] By this system, millers in departments with more supply than demand could sell the excess to ONIC.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In practice, this meant that the higher-quality flour would be delivered to local bakers and lower-quality flour would be exported to other departments.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Thus, departments with net flour deficits, like the Gard department in which Pont-Saint-Esprit was located, would be supplied with lower-quality flour from other departments via ONIC, with the bakers having virtually no choice of the provenance or quality of their flour.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In the weeks preceding the outbreak, several villages near Pont-Saint-Esprit reported outbreaks of food poisoning via bread.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] These outbreaks were all linked to bakeries that made their bread with most if not all of their flour supplied by the mill of Maurice Maillet, in Saint-Martin-la-Riviere.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The symptoms reported were milder than those reported in Pont-Saint-Esprit.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] At Issirac, at least 20 people reported cutaneous eruptions, diarrhea, vomiting and headaches.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Similar symptoms were reported in Laval-Saint-Roman.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Multiple families were reported sick in Goudargues and Lamotte-du-Rhone.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In Connaux, the town's baker received reports from his clients that they believed his bread was causing violent diarrhea.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] He reported that his family, as well as himself, were all suffering from the same afflictions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The baker was quick to blame his flour, which he described as “bad, forming a sticky dough with acid fermentation” and which made gray and sticky bread.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In Saint-Geniès-de-Comolas, the town's mayor was alerted by one of the town's two bakers that he received flour that was gray and full of worms.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The mayor banned making bread with that flour, and referred the situation to the region's prefect, as well as to the driver that delivered the flour.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The delivery driver, Jean Bousquet, sent the prefect a copy of a remark made to his employer, the miller's union in Nimes, on 9 August.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The note said that "almost every baker of Centre de Bagnols-sur-Cèze has complained of the quality of the flour provided by Mr.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Following the incident at Connaux, Bousquet requested immediate written instructions from his employer regarding the situation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] On the 13th of August, he requested that samples be taken to determine if the flour was contaminated.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] During this period, 42 bakers complained of the flour delivered by Bousquet.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] On 16 August 1951, the local offices of the town's two doctors filled with patients reporting similar food poisoning symptoms: nausea, vomiting, cold chills, heat waves.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] These symptoms eventually worsened, with added hallucinatory crises and convulsions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The situation in the town deteriorated in the following days.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] On the night of 24 August, a man believed himself to be an aeroplane and died by jumping from a second-story window, and an 11-year-old boy tried to strangle his mother.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] One of the town's two doctors would name the night *nuit d'apocalypse;* apocalyptic night.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Doctors Vieu and Gabbai investigated the epidemiology of the disease.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] On 19 August, they came to the conclusion that bread was to blame; all patients interrogated had purchased their bread at the Briand bakery in Pont-Saint-Esprit.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In a family from a neighboring village, four of whose nine members fell ill, all members who ate bread from the Briand bakery fell ill, whereas none of the others who ate bread from another bakery did.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Another family shared a loaf of Briand's bread among five of its seven members, the others preferring biscottes, with only the five falling ill.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] On the morning of the 20th, the health service, the prefecture, the prosecutor of the Republic and the police were notified.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Roch Briand was interrogated, and the sickness in the town was blamed on his bread.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The police investigation would eventually center on the second of three batches of bread made at Briand's bakery on the day of 16 August.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The flour composition of each batch varied, as having run out of flour during the preparation of the second batch, Briand had borrowed flour from two other local bakers, Jaussent and Fallavet.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Briand's assistant stated that when he picked up flour from Jaussent, the baker was out ill, and that he took the flour from his assistant instead.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Both Briand and his assistant agreed that the first batch was constituted of the previous day's flour mixed with flour borrowed from Jaussent.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] They disagreed on the second and third batches.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Whereas Briand stated that the second was made with Jaussent's flour and the third with Fallavet's flour, the assistant stated that both latter batches were made with a mix of the two.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The investigation led police to interrogate many of the town's residents, who gave inconsistent ratings of Briand's tainted batch.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Some reported that the taste was perfectly normal, while others reported chemical smells (one described an odor of gasoline, another of bleach).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Some reported that the bread looked normal, while others stated that its appearance was grayish.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] On the 23rd of August, a judge of inquiry opened a formal investigation, and tasked commissaire Georges Sigaud with finding the cause of the mass poisoning event.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The tainted bread made by Briand was made with only four ingredients: flour, yeast, water and salt.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] All of the ingredients but the flour could be easily discounted as sources of the illness.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The water used to make the bread was from a municipal source, the same that also supplied the rest of the village.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Both the salt and the yeast used by Briand were sourced from the same suppliers as all other bakers in the region, and subsequent testing of the supplies found no toxicity.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The investigation of the provenance of the flour led Sigaud to the UM-Gard flour distribution centre, in Bagnols-sur-Cèze.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In an interrogation that lasted multiple hours, Maurice Maillet denied mixing rye (which is highly susceptible to ergot) into his flour, stating that he opted instead to cut his product with 2% of bean flour.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] This was unusual, given that owing to a shortage of wheat, the grain control board, ONIC, had mandated that rye flour be mixed in.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] However, in the Vienne department, rye of good quality was often more expensive than wheat, and accordingly, bean flour was authorised by ONIC as a replacement.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Despite this, it came to light that the supply of grains to be milled for export was sometimes mixed with grains milled in an informal agreement called *échangisme*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Under this type of agreement, often practiced at the time, a farmer would bring a baker grain he grew himself in exchange for bread that would later be made with his grain.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The baker would bring the grain to the miller, who would mill it.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The miller and baker would each take a cut for sale.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] During the interrogation, Maillet admitted that he had made a deal with a baker, Guy Bruère, who had brought in bags to be milled.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Since this was near the end of the season, the bags were filled with leftover grain that sometimes contained a high proportion of rye.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The rye was not the only problem with the flour, as the miller also noted the presence of weevils, mites and dust.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The baker was concerned that he would lose business should he refuse the grain on the basis of quality.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Despite the miller having noticed the low quality of the grains, he agreed to exchange the grain for a lower quantity of flour already milled from grain marked for export.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Given that the quantity of lower-quality grain was much lower than that of the grain for export, the miller thought that it would be possible to mix it all without reducing the overall quality of the flour.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] On August 31, around 14:30, Sigaud addressed the media, announcing the arrests of Maillet and Bruère for involuntary manslaughter and involuntary injuries arising from their negligence in trading improper flour.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Further arrests were made in the following days: an employee of Maillet, André Bertrand, was arrested, but released on bail as he was the head of a family of nine whose wife was about to give birth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The owners of the bakery at which Bruère was employed, Clothaire and Denise Audidier, were also arrested for infractions of fiscal legislation and of legislation governing wheat and flour.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Shortly after the incident, in September 1951, Dr.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Gabbai and colleagues published a paper in the *British Medical Journal* declaring that "the outbreak of poisoning" was produced by ergot fungus.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The victims appeared to have one common connection.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] They had eaten bread from the bakery of Roch Briand, who was subsequently blamed for having used flour made from contaminated rye.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Animals who had eaten the bread were also found to have perished.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] According to reports at the time, the flour had been contaminated by the fungus *Claviceps purpurea* (ergot), which produces alkaloids that are structurally similar to the hallucinogenic drug lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Later investigations suggested mercury poisoning due to the use of Panogen or other fungicides to treat grain and seeds.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] This type of contamination was considered owing to the presence of fluorescent stains on the outside of some used empty flour bags returned to the distributor.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Panogen was sold containing a red colorant as a safety measure, to ensure that seeds coated with it would be used only for planting.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Subsequent scientific tests showed that this coloring would not penetrate flour bags but that the active ingredient could do so.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] This would allow contamination of the flour, but it would appear to be limited to the bags.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Further testing showed that if bread were to be baked using Panogen-contaminated flour, the rising of the bread could be partially or totally inhibited, depending on the concentration.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] This hypothesis was considered thoroughly in a French civil trial arising from the accident, with the contamination mechanism being a train wagon carrying flour that could have previously carried concentrated cylinders of Panogen intended for agricultural uses.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] It was later discovered that pre-treating the seeds in Panogen could lead to mercury accumulation in the plants growing from those seeds.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] For this reason, Panogen, made by a Swedish company, was banned in Sweden in 1966.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] A revised version of the ban, in 1970, would prohibit the exportation of Panogen, leading to its removal from the market.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In 1982, a French researcher suggested *Aspergillus fumigatus*, a toxic fungus produced in grain silos, as a potential culprit.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Historian Steven Kaplan's 2008 book *Le Pain Maudit* states that the poisoning might have been caused by nitrogen trichloride used to artificially (and illegally) bleach flour.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] In his 2009 book *A Terrible Mistake*, the investigative journalist Hank P.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Albarelli Jr writes that the Special Operations Division of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) tested the use of LSD on the population of Pont-Saint-Esprit as part of its MKNAOMI biological warfare program, in a field test called "Project SPAN".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] According to Albarelli, this is based on CIA documents held in the US National Archives and a document supplied to the 1975 Rockefeller Commission that investigated CIA activities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] The attribution of the poisoning to the CIA in Albarelli's book has been criticized.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Historian Steven Kaplan, author of an earlier book about the events, said that this would be "clinically incoherent: LSD takes effects in just a few hours, whereas the inhabitants showed symptoms only after 36 hours or more.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] According to *Mary's Mosaic* by Peter Janney, the dispersal over the village took place using a crop-duster type airplane, as had happened elsewhere with U.S.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Army aerosol tests over civilian neighbourhoods such as Operation LAC and related Army and CIA programs based at chemical and biological warfare laboratory of Fort Detrick, Maryland.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] *A Terrible Mistake* also mentions of a supposed low-flying unmarked aircraft on the morning of the outbreak.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] For his assertions Albarelli uses transcripts of a conversation between the CIA and the Swiss laboratory Sandoz personnel, where LSD was invented, located 100 miles from Pont-Saint-Esprit in over the border city of Basel.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Barbara Comyns wrote her third novel, *Who Was Changed and Who Was Dead* (1954), after reading about the poisoning.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1951-pont-saint-esprit-mass-poisoning] Sophie Mackintosh's third novel, *Cursed Bread* (2023) is based on the poisoning.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The **1967 British flying saucer hoax** was originally thought to be the landing of six mysterious "spaceships" that occurred across Southern England on Monday, 4 September 1967.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] A major police and army response followed the discovery of the "spacecraft", which were 54 inches (1.4 m) long, 30 inches (0.76 m) wide and 20 inches (0.51 m) deep, weighed 100 pounds (45 kg) and emitted an electronic noise.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The hoax was undertaken by aircraft engineering apprentices from the Royal Aircraft Establishment (RAE) at Farnborough.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The hoax had been planned in January 1967 to be part of RAE Farnborough Apprentices' upcoming Rag Week.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The apprentices moulded the half-shells of their flying saucers in glass-fibre-reinforced polyester resin (fibreglass), with an aluminium-powder-impregnated gel-coat (outside surface).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] Once joined and polished, the shells appeared to be a smooth, solid form of dull aluminium with no joints, holes or protrusions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] Prior to joining the half-shells, the (then) lower half of each saucer was part-filled with a smelly fermenting flour and water paste.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] An electronic oscillator with loudspeaker was installed in the upper blister, to make eerie sounds when the saucer was moved or flipped over.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] In small groups, the Rag Committee drove to preselected locations in the dead of night to place the saucers on open ground with good public access.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The 'drop' positions were evenly spaced, close to the line of 51.5 degrees latitude, roughly between the Thames estuary and Bristol Channel.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] One member of each delivery party had a plausible reason for being in the area, should they be challenged.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] Some of the saucers were left silent, and others flipped over causing them to emit 'disturbing' electronic sound.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] At the time, none of the perpetrators was challenged or identified.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] When each of the saucers was later reported to the police, they were cordoned off.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The British Army's southern command, several police forces, army bomb disposal units, and RAF helicopters were mobilised.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The Ministry of Defence was informed and the army blew up the saucer found at Chippenham.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The one on the Isle of Sheppey was removed by helicopter.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] Another was sent to the Atomic Weapons Establishment at Aldermaston and one to the guided weapons division of the British Aircraft Corporation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] When one of the saucers was drilled into, the mixture inside exploded, covering police officers in foul-smelling slime.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The masterminds were Christopher Southall and Roger Palmer, both aged 21.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The motive for the hoax was to gain publicity for the RAE Apprentices' Rag Week, to boost fundraising.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The hoax received extensive media attention, in Britain and abroad.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] The apprentices did not think the hoax would create such a media storm but several were later interviewed on television.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] They revealed the hoax the same day as the saucers were found.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1967-british-flying-saucer-hoax] No action was taken against the hoaxers, and they raised £2,000 for charity.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] On 19 October 1986, a Tupolev Tu-134 jetliner with a Soviet crew carrying President Samora Machel and 43 others from Mbala, Zambia to the Mozambican capital Maputo crashed at Mbuzini, South Africa.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Nine passengers and one crew member survived the crash, but President Machel and 33 others died, including several ministers and senior officials of the Mozambican government.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A board of inquiry blamed the captain for failing to react to the ground proximity warning system.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Another theory was that the crew had set the aircraft's VOR receivers to the wrong frequency, causing them to receive signals from a different airport, or even that a false beacon had been used to lure the crew off course.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] While there was widespread suspicion in other nations that South Africa, which was hostile towards Machel's government at the time, was involved in the incident, no conclusive evidence was ever presented to support that allegation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The aircraft involved, manufactured by Tupolev on 19 August 1980, was a Tupolev Tu-134A-3, registered as C9-CAA, with serial number 63457.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] It had accumulated about 1,105 flying hours since the first flight, and had undergone its last major inspection in August 1984 in the Soviet Union.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Service records indicated that it had been properly maintained, and data recovered from the Digital Flight Data Recorder (DFDR) showed the aircraft and all its systems were operating normally.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In command was 48-year-old Captain Yuri Viktorovich Novodran.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In total, he had logged 13,056 hours of flying time, 7,523 of which were logged on the Tu-134.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] His co-pilot was 29-year-old First Officer Igor Petrovich Kartamyshev.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In total, he had logged 3,790 hours of flying time, 2,380 of which were logged on the Tu-134.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The flight engineer was 37-year-old Vladimir B.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Novoselov, logging all 6,203 of his total flight hours on the Tu-134.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The navigator was 48-year-old Oleg Nikolaevich Kudryashov with 12,942 hours of flying time, 6,074 of which on the Tu-134 and the radio operator was 39-year-old Anatoly Shulipov, having logged 14,370 hours of flying time, of which 1,450 logged on the Tu-134.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] All of the mentioned were Soviet state employees operating the aircraft for the Mozambican government.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] They were well experienced in both day and night flying in Mozambique and in landings at Maputo airport.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] On the morning of 19 October, Machel boarded the flight at Maputo, and, after a refuelling stop in Lusaka, Zambia, arrived at Mbala, Zambia at 11:00.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] After the meeting with Kaunda and Dos Santos, Machel and his party re-boarded the aircraft and departed Mbala at 18:38 for a non-stop return to Maputo.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The weather forecast for the flight was favourable, with an estimated time of arrival of 21:25.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At 20:46, the flight made its first radio contact with Maputo air traffic control (ATC), reporting its position and that it was continuing towards the Maputo VHF Omnidirectional Range (VOR) navigation beacon while maintaining an altitude of 35,000 feet (11,000 m).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At 21:02, the crew radioed that they were ready to begin descent, and were instructed by Maputo air traffic control to report reaching 3,000 feet (910 m) or when the runway lights were in sight, they began their descent for an ILS approach to runway 23.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Over the next eight minutes, the aircraft maintained its required track toward Maputo with minor lateral deviations.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Then, at 21:10, the aircraft turned away from Maputo to the right, lasting almost one minute in duration resulting in a heading change from 184° to 221°.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At this time, the cockpit voice recorder (CVR) recorded the navigator stating the distance remaining to Maputo as 100 kilometres (62 mi; 54 nmi), then a comment from the captain about the turn, and the navigator's response that the "VOR indicates that way".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At around 21:15, the navigator stated that the distance to Maputo was 60 kilometres (37 mi; 32 nmi).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Over the next few minutes, there were several comments from the crew indicating that they believed the navigational aids at Maputo were unavailable.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The captain then stated that "there is no Maputo" and "electrical power is off, chaps!", while the navigator reported that the instrument landing system (ILS) and distance measuring equipment (DME) were switched off and that the non-directional beacons (NDBs) were not working.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Shortly after 21:18, the aircraft reached 910 metres (3,000 ft) in its descent, and the crew informed the Maputo controller that they were maintaining that altitude.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] However, the flight continued to descend.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Maputo controller granted clearance for an ILS approach to runway 23, but after the flight crew reported the ILS out of service, the controller changed the clearance to a visual approach to runway 05.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] During this time, the navigator stated the distance to Maputo as 25–30 km (16–19 mi; 13–16 nmi); the captain remarked that something was wrong and the co-pilot said that the runway was not lit.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The crew radioed the Maputo controller and asked him to "check your runway lights".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Around 21:21, the navigator stated the range to Maputo as 18–20 km (11–12 mi; 9.7–10.8 nmi), and the flight repeated its request to Maputo to check runway lights.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Upon reaching an altitude of 796 metres (2,611 ft) AGL, the ground proximity warning system (GPWS) sounded and remained on and, although the captain cursed, the descent continued.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] During the last 22 seconds of the flight, the crew twice more radioed Maputo about the runway lights, affirming that they were not in sight, which was eventually acknowledged by the Maputo controller.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Meanwhile, the captain stated "cloudy, cloudy, cloudy" and the navigator exclaimed "no, no, there's nowhere to go, there's no NDBs, nothing!".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The captain then added "Neither NDBs, nor ILS!", which were the last words recorded on the CVR.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The aircraft first impacted terrain at 21:21:39, approximately 65 kilometres (40 mi; 35 nmi) west of Maputo in a hilly region at an elevation of 666 metres (2,185 ft).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At the time of the accident, it was a very dark night, a few minutes before moonrise.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The last weather report passed to the aircraft indicated 10 kilometres (5.4 nmi; 6.2 mi) of visibility with 3/8 cloud cover at 550 metres (1,800 ft).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] After being unable to contact the flight on the radio, the Maputo controller alerted authorities and the Mozambican military units prepared for search and rescue.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Since the last radio communication with the aircraft had been four minutes before its estimated time of arrival, the initial search area was defined around Maputo.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Throughout the rest of the night and early morning, many helictopers were out to search for the missing flight, and, in addition, a marine search of Maputo Bay was carried out, all without success.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The actual accident site was in a remote, inaccessible corner of South Africa, approximately 150 metres (500 ft) from the Mozambican border.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The left wing hit a tree and the aircraft broke up before sliding down a hill, distributing the wreckage over a debris field 846 metres (2,776 ft) in length.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A police officer was alerted at approximately 23:00 by a villager from Mbuzini, and the first responder to the scene was a member of the Komatipoort police station who arrived at 23:40.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The first medical personnel reached the site at 01:00.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Shortly after 04:00, a helicopter and medical crew from the South African Air Force Base Hoedspruit arrived and evacuated the survivors to Nelspruit hospital.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Of the five members of the flight crew, only the flight engineer survived.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] All four Mozambican cabin crew were killed, as were 26 of the 35 passengers.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] According to the autopsy conducted by a South African pathologist, Machel died instantly.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Besides Machel, the dead included Marxist scholar and diplomat Aquino de Bragança, Machel's possible successor Fernando Honwana, press secretary Muradali Mamadhussein, photo-journalist Daniel Maquinasse, and transport minister Alcantara Santos.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] One survivor died 2+1⁄2 months after the crash from his injuries.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Pik Botha was alerted to the crash at 04:30 by a phone call from Minister Louis le Grange, who stated that Machel and 30-40 passengers on board had been killed.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Pik Botha reported that he telephoned and informed State President P.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Both of them agreed that, considering the sensitivity of the situation, Pik Botha should accompany officials investigating the crash site.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At 06:50, South Africa first notified the Mozambican Government that a plane headed to Maputo had crashed in South African territory near the border.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The first public indication of the tragedy was when Radio Mozambique switched to funeral music at 08:30 and Marcelino dos Santos, a member of the ruling FRELIMO Party announced President Machel's aircraft had not returned to Maputo as scheduled the previous evening.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Dos Santos said authorities were analyzing the situation and appealed for calm and vigilance.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Mozambican security minister, Sérgio Vieira, traveled to Mbuzini with Pik Botha, and proceeded to the crash site and personally identified Machel's body.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] FRELIMO issued a second communique that evening confirming Machel's death.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] It did not accuse South Africa directly, however it did suggest that the crash had been criminal in origin.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] While over the following days and weeks, Mozambican government officials would continue to refrain from overt statements of South African complicity, many other leaders in Africa stated outright that the apartheid government was responsible.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Violence erupted in Harare, Zimbabwe, when cars driven by whites were attacked by angry demonstrators, prompting an editorial rebuke in Mozambique that declared that Machel had been committed to a non-racial Africa.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] After lying in state at Maputo City Hall, Machel's funeral on 28 October was attended by more than 100 foreign delegations.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Eulogized as a fighter who died in the struggle against apartheid, banners in the crowd made reference to South African involvement in the crash.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] On scene the South African police located and took custody of the cockpit voice recorder (CVR) and flight data recorder (FDR) (the aircraft was equipped with both digital and magnetic FDRs).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] According to Pik Botha, this was due to suspicions that they could be tampered with.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Media access to the site was limited to a team from SABC-TV.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Autopsies were conducted on only the four dead flight crew and three others and the bodies returned to Mozambique without the approval of the SACAA.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] On arrival, Mozambican minister Sérgio Vieira asked for the documents that were taken from the aircraft to be handed to him.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The SA commissioner of police, Johann Coetzee, had already made copies of these, and the documents were transferred to Vieira.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In accordance with the South African Air Control Act, aircraft accidents are required to be investigated by the SA Department of Transport.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Thus, Pik Botha consulted Hendrik Schoeman of the Department of Transport, once Machel's death was confirmed.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] After Botha and Schoeman had visited the crash site, Botha cited special circumstances and other international protocols as reasons to become involved.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In a press conference on 6 November, Botha announced that a document retrieved from the plane revealed a Mozambican-Zimbabwean plot to topple the Malawian government.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The three international teams signed a protocol of secrecy on 14 November 1986 as Botha's selective announcements were straining relations between the teams and governments.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Nevertheless, Botha reported to *Beeld* newspaper on 24 November 1986 that he had listened to Maputo air traffic control's recordings and studied their transcription.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] He had acquired them from a foreign affairs representative in the South African team.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Director Renee van Zyl of the South African Civil Aviation Bureau served a writ on Botha and the SAP, and received the two recorders at 15:45 on 11 November 1986.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] On 24 October 1986, a 26-member Soviet and Mozambican delegation travelled from Maputo to Komatipoort to join the South African team investigating the crash.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Eventually, agreement was reached for representatives of South Africa, Mozambique and the Soviet Union to jointly examine the CVR tapes under Swiss auspices in Zürich.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Pik Botha would later state that on his recommendation, due to the mounting suspicions of South African culpability in the crash, the services of three foreign individuals were obtained, and these persons became three of the six members of the Board of Inquiry.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The three South African board members included J.J.S.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Germishuys, former South African Commissioner for Civil Aviation, and Pieter van Hoven, chairman of the Airlines Association of South Africa.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The inquiry was chaired by Cecil Margo, a member of the South African Supreme Court who had participated in several other high-profile aircraft accident investigations previously.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Board members participated in the earlier fact-finding portion of the investigation, and conducted public hearings at the Supreme Court in Johannesburg from 20 January until 26 January 1987.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The board then adjourned to analyze the evidence and reach conclusions as to cause.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The board concluded that the 37° turn was executed by the navigator using the autopilot's Doppler navigation mode, which when set maintained the desired heading while making corrections for wind drift.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The navigator performed this turn after he saw the VOR signal indicating that the aircraft had intercepted the Maputo VOR 45° radial, the compass direction from Maputo on which the crew intended to turn and approach for a landing on runway 23.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] However, the turn actually put the aircraft on a path following a 45° radial from the VOR beacon at Matsapa Airport, Swaziland.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Discounting the possibility of a false VOR beacon, an analysis of which was included in an appendix, the board considered it probable that the flight crew had inadvertently set the first of two VOR receivers on board to the Matsapa VOR frequency.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The board considered it "quite likely" that after the turn the captain re-tuned first VOR receiver to the ILS frequency, as the instrument was found in this state after the crash.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] For the final stages of flight, the aircraft was not following any VOR signal; instead the autopilot was tracking the 221° heading the navigator had set earlier during the turn.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The post-accident settings of the second VOR receiver showed that it was displaying the aircraft's position relative to Maputo and was correctly set to the Maputo VOR frequency, but was apparently not being used to guide the autopilot nor was it being monitored by the crew.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The captain's initial erroneous assumption that Maputo had had an electrical blackout was never reconsidered by the crew, despite evidence to the contrary.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Throughout the descent, the crew were in radio contact with the Maputo controller, who therefore had electrical power, and backup power generators were standard equipment for airport navigational aids.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] All the navigation aids at Maputo were determined by the board to be working at the time of the accident, although the aircraft was flying too far away and too low to receive the ILS and NDB signals.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] When announcing the distance remaining to Maputo, the navigator was apparently referring to the Doppler navigation system, which was not accurate, rather than the DME equipment available on board which correctly displayed the distance to the Maputo DME beacon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The crew were criticised for failing to perform any checklist items or navigational aid identification, as well as for the distractions and non-essential conversations in the cockpit during the descent into Maputo.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] As a consequence of not announcing to the other crew members which navigational aids were being used, or the frequencies being set, mistakes could not be corrected by others through "cross-checking".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Regarding it essential that the relatively large crew in the cockpit work as a well-integrated team, the board concluded that "demonstrably they had not".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The board found that use of non-standard phraseology between the Maputo controller and the crew led to confusion about the status of the ILS signal and whether the runway lights were on.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The flight crew's repeated requests to "check runway lights" were interpreted by the controller, based on the use of the word 'check' in civil aviation, as confirmation by the crew that they had the runway lights in sight.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The aircraft had not refueled at Mbala before departing and did not have enough fuel remaining to reach the intended alternative airport in Beira, Mozambique by the time it reached Maputo.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] This may have greatly increased the pressure on the crew to continue with the landing approach to Maputo despite the difficulties encountered.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The only reaction to the warning by the GPWS, which sounded for 32 seconds, was the captain exclaiming "Damn it!" and a very slight nose-up pitch of the aircraft.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The board concluded that even just seconds before the impact, had the crew performed the required procedures for a GPWS alert when flying over hilly or unknown terrain, quickly raising the nose and increasing power, this would have prevented the crash.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The report was endorsed unanimously by the six members of the board and submitted to the South African Minister of Transport Affairs on 2 July 1987.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Mozambican delegation, representing the State of registry of the aircraft, had a right by international treaty to review a draft of the report and submit their comments for consideration.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Mozambican team provided 11 pages of suggested corrections to the draft, some of which were adopted by the Board.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In their submission, the Mozambican delegation stated that according to the survivors the South African Police searched the aircraft for documents rather than tending to the injured passengers.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Mozambique also provided a technical report prepared by Ron Chippindale of the New Zealand Office of Air Accidents Investigations examining the possibility of tampering with or replacing the genuine Maputo VOR signal with a decoy.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] His conclusions were that it would be "simple" to set up a mobile VOR.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] However, in order to effectively replace the genuine signal, the Maputo VOR would have to be turned off.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Soviet Union, the state of manufacture of the aircraft, was given a draft of the final report and a chance to review and submit comments in accordance with ICAO convention.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In their remarks, the Soviet Union reiterated their endorsement of the previously agreed upon factual information contained in the draft.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] They ended their remarks with a full rejection of the draft, calling it "worthless", and instead offering their own analysis and conclusions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Soviet delegation stated the theory that the crew had mistakenly selected the Matsapa VOR was contradicted by the known settings of the onboard navigation equipment and the timing of the turn.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] They said that the data recovered from the magnetic flight data recorder did not correspond to the path of an aircraft following the signal from the Matsapa VOR.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] According to the Soviets, the other navigational aids at Maputo were not strong enough to reach the aircraft and were of no help to the flight crew.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A LAM Airlines Boeing 737 flying at around the same time as the accident aircraft reported receiving the Maputo VOR signal unusually early, at a distance of about 350 kilometres (220 mi; 190 nmi).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Soviets stated that this was actually the false decoy beacon that was working with a higher signal level that the actual Maputo VOR.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Soviets stated that there was an earlier ground proximity warning system (GPWS) alert about 4+1⁄2 minutes before impact which was triggered by the signal from the decoy VOR beacon, and this false alert was interpreted by the flight crew as a systems fault in the GPWS.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Receipt by the flight crew of the visual landing clearance from the Maputo controller implied permission to descend below 910 metres (3,000 ft) according to ICAO procedures.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] When the GPWS sounded shortly before impact the crew, doubting its reliability, disregarded it as false, and believing they were over the low terrain continued their descent.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Suspicion of a false beacon in the Lebombos mountains was first expressed by South African helicopter pilots on the morning following the crash, followed by a similar suggestion in an anonymous call to UPI by a supposed SAAF officer, a day later.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The pilots' speculative remark was revealed to Sérgio Vieira, Mozambique's minister of security, in a rash comment by South African police commissioner Johann Coetzee.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Neither the Mozambican or Russian teams however, nor any witness testimony given, supplied any evidence or direct allegation concerning a secondary beacon to the Margo commission.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The Margo commission's draft report then proposed Matsapa airfield's VOR, combined with pilot error, as playing a likely role in the trajectory followed by the aircraft.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The USSR delegation disputed this, saying the signal was obscured by mountains.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A breakdown in communications followed, causing General Earp of the South African Air Force to authorise military pilots to penetrate Mozambique airspace to test the Matsapa theory.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] They returned with confirmation, though the final report relied on additional testimonies of commercial pilots who flew on C9-CAA's track.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] They likewise confirmed clear VOR signals from Matsapa.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Mozambican pilot Dias, who supported the Matsapa theory, illustrated his interpretation of events to Mozambican officials on a flight from Lisbon to Maputo.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] However, Mozambican authorities remained unconvinced and suspended air controller de Jesus on 5 May 1998, for allegedly having been bribed to tamper with Maputo airport's beacon on the night of the crash.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A special investigation into Machel's death was carried out by the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The report, published in 2001, is available on the T&RC website volume 2-page 494.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] It was found that "The investigations conducted by the Commission raised a number of questions, including the possibility of a false beacon and the absence of a warning from the South African authorities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The TRC investigation took place in camera and without any aviation specialist being present.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The testimony was further led by a prominent radio journalist rather than a judge.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The TRC's investigation did not find conclusive evidence to support or refute either of the earlier reports.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The TRC report concluded that the questions of a false beacon and the absence of a warning from the South African authorities require "further investigation by an appropriate structure".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A police video in the TRC's possession shows South African foreign minister Pik Botha telling journalists at the crash site that President Samora Machel and others killed in the crash were his and President P.W.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Botha's "very good friends", and that their deaths were a tragedy for South Africa.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In January 2003, the *Sowetan Sunday World* reported that an apartheid era killer and former CCB member, Hans Louw, serving a 28-year term at Baviaanspoort Prison near Pretoria, South Africa, had confessed to participating in a plot to kill Machel.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A false radio navigational beacon would have been used to lure the aircraft off course, with Louw forming part of an alleged backup team to shoot the aircraft down if it did not crash.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] The newspaper also alleged that another of the plotters, former Rhodesian Selous Scout, Edwin Mudingi, supported Louw's claim.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] However, after an investigation by the Scorpions, a South African special police unit, it was reported in July 2003 and in October 2008 that they could find no evidence for South African complicity.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In a television documentary written and produced by South African TV journalist Johann Abrahams, Louw says: "So, when the plane reached that hill it was already lower than 1,000 feet [300 m].
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] And the wheels to prepare to land was (sic) already out.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] “NAVIGATOR: NO, NO, THERE’S NOWHERE TO GO, NO NDBs, THERE IS NOTHING.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] South African Minister of Safety and Security, Charles Nqakula announced on 2 February 2006 that the Machel death crash inquiry would be reopened.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] He told reporters in Parliament that all of South Africa's law enforcement agencies were expected to be involved in the probe, in co-operation with their Mozambican counterparts.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In October 2006, the enquiry was expected to "be wrapped up before the end of the year" but there seems to be no further information available.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A Mbuzini wreath laying ceremony on 17 October 1986 was attended by Graça Machel and addressed by Nelson Mandela.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Mandela declared the initial simple memorial a South African national monument and hailed Machel as a universal hero whose life exemplified the highest ideals of internationalism and universality.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Mandela cautiously claimed that the precise chain of events leading to Machel's death were uncertain and elusive, and repeated an earlier promise that no stone would be left unturned to establish the full truth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A Samora Machel Monument was erected at the crash site.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Designed by Mozambican architect, Jose Forjaz, at a cost to the South African government of 1.5 million Rand (US$300,000), the monument comprises 35 whistling wind pipes to symbolise each of the lives lost in the accident.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] It was inaugurated on 19 January 1999 by Nelson Mandela, his wife Graça, and by President Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At the 20th anniversary of the crash, on 19 October 2006, South African president Thabo Mbeki declared the memorial a national heritage site.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In November 2006, Jacob Zuma, then ANC deputy president, said that Machel's death was unusual.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] At the Mandela-Machel wedding ceremony on 18 July 1998, Mandela was reported to have announced that Samora Machel was murdered, without reference to the South African board of enquiry's findings.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] Graça Machel believes this crash was no accident and attempted to track down her late husband's alleged killers.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] In May 1999, Graça Machel said in an interview on SABC TV's *News Maker* programme that she remained convinced the apartheid government was responsible, and challenged former foreign minister Pik Botha to "come clean" about Samora Machel's death.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] A study in the Quarterly Journal of Economics reached the conclusions that the crash had immediate wider repercussions for Mozambique's economy.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/1986-mozambican-tupolev-tu-134-crash] An annual 7.7% decline in GDP under Machel's communist nationalisation policies, reverted to growth averaging 2.4% per annum under the freer, multi-party democracy in the tenure of his successor, Joaquim Chissano.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The **2012 phenomenon** was a range of eschatological beliefs that cataclysmic or transformative events would occur on or around 21 December 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Various astronomical alignments and numerological formulae were proposed for this date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] A New Age interpretation held that the date marked the start of a period during which Earth and its inhabitants would undergo a positive physical or spiritual transformation, and that 21 December 2012 would mark the beginning of a new era.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Others suggested that the date marked the end of the world or a similar catastrophe.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Scholars from various disciplines quickly dismissed predictions of cataclysmic events as they arose.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Mayan scholars stated that no classic Mayan accounts forecast impending doom, and the idea that the Long Count calendar ends in 2012 misrepresented Mayan history and culture.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers rejected the various proposed doomsday scenarios as pseudoscience, having been refuted by elementary astronomical observations.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] December 2012 marked the conclusion of a *bʼakʼtun*—a time period in the Mesoamerican Long Count calendar, used in Mesoamerica prior to the arrival of Europeans.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Although the Long Count was most likely invented by the Olmec, it has become closely associated with the Maya civilization, whose classic period lasted from 250 to 900 AD.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The writing system of the classic Maya has been substantially deciphered, meaning that a text corpus of their written and inscribed material has survived from before the Spanish conquest of Yucatán.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Thus, the Maya date of 8.3.2.10.15 represents 8 bʼakʼtuns, 3 kʼatuns, 2 tuns, 10 uinals and 15 days.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] There is a strong tradition of "world ages" in Maya literature, but the record has been distorted, leaving several possibilities open to interpretation.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] According to the *Popol Vuh*, a compilation of the creation accounts of the Kʼicheʼ Maya of the Colonial-era highlands, the current world is the fourth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The *Popol Vuh* describes the gods first creating three failed worlds, followed by a successful fourth world in which humanity was placed.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In the Maya Long Count, the previous world ended after 13 bʼakʼtuns, or roughly 5,125 years.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Long Count's "zero date" was set at a point in the past marking the end of the third world and the beginning of the current one, which corresponds to 11 August 3114 BC in the proleptic Gregorian calendar.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This means that the fourth world reached the end of its 13th bʼakʼtun, or Maya date 13.0.0.0.0, on 21 December 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 1957, Mayanist and astronomer Maud Worcester Makemson wrote that "the completion of a Great Period of 13 bʼakʼtuns would have been of the utmost significance to the Maya." In 1966, Michael D.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Coe wrote in *The Maya* that "there is a suggestion ... that Armageddon would overtake the degenerate peoples of the world and all creation on the final day of the 13th [bʼakʼtun].
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Coe's interpretation was repeated by other scholars through the early 1990s.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In contrast, later researchers said that, while the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun would perhaps be a cause for celebration, it did not mark the end of the calendar.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] "There is nothing in the Maya or Aztec or ancient Mesoamerican prophecy to suggest that they prophesied a sudden or major change of any sort in 2012," said Mayanist scholar Mark Van Stone.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] "The notion of a 'Great Cycle' coming to an end is completely a modern invention." In 1990, Mayanist scholars Linda Schele and David Freidel argued that the Maya "did not conceive this to be the end of creation, as many have suggested".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Susan Milbrath, curator of Latin American Art and Archaeology at the Florida Museum of Natural History, stated that, "We have no record or knowledge that [the Maya] would think the world would come to an end" in 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Wyllys Andrews V, director of the Tulane University Middle American Research Institute.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Maya were looking for a guarantee that nothing would change.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Several prominent individuals representing Maya of Guatemala decried the suggestion that the world would end with the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Ricardo Cajas, president of the *Colectivo de Organizaciones Indígenas de Guatemala*, said the date did not represent an end of humanity but that the new cycle "supposes changes in human consciousness".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Martín Sacalxot, of the office of Guatemala's Human Rights Ombudsman (*Procurador de los Derechos Humanos*), said that the end of the calendar has nothing to do with the end of the world or the year 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The European association of the Maya with eschatology dates back to the time of Christopher Columbus, who was compiling a work called *Libro de las profecías* during the voyage in 1502 when he first heard about the "Maia" on Guanaja, an island off the north coast of Honduras.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Influenced by the writings of Bishop Pierre d'Ailly, Columbus believed that his discovery of "most distant" lands (and, by extension, the Maya themselves) was prophesied and would bring about the Apocalypse.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] End-times fears were widespread during the early years of the Spanish Conquest as the result of popular astrological predictions in Europe of a second Great Flood for the year 1524.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In the 1900s, German scholar Ernst Förstemann interpreted the last page of the Dresden Codex as a representation of the end of the world in a cataclysmic flood.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] He made reference to the destruction of the world and an apocalypse, though he made no reference to the 13th bʼakʼtun or 2012 and it was not clear that he was referring to a future event.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] His ideas were repeated by archaeologist Sylvanus Morley, who directly paraphrased Förstemann and added his own embellishments, writing, "Finally, on the last page of the manuscript, is depicted the Destruction of the World ...
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Here, indeed, is portrayed with a graphic touch the final all-engulfing cataclysm" in the form of a great flood.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] These comments were later repeated in Morley's book, *The Ancient Maya*, the first edition of which was published in 1946.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] It is not certain what significance the classic Maya gave to the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Most classic Maya inscriptions are strictly historical and do not make any prophetic declarations.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Two items in the Maya classical corpus do mention the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun: Tortuguero Monument 6 and La Corona Hieroglyphic Stairway 12.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Tortuguero site, which lies in southernmost Tabasco, Mexico, dates from the 7th century AD and consists of a series of inscriptions mostly in honor of the contemporary ruler Bahlam Ahau.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] One inscription, known as Tortuguero Monument 6, is the only inscription known to refer to bʼakʼtun 13 in any detail.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Very little is known about the god Bʼolon Yokteʼ.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] According to an article by Mayanists Markus Eberl and Christian Prager in *British Anthropological Reports*, his name is composed of the elements "nine", ʼOK-teʼ (the meaning of which is unknown), and "god".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Confusion in classical period inscriptions suggests that the name was already ancient and unfamiliar to contemporary scribes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] He also appears in inscriptions from Palenque, Usumacinta, and La Mar as a god of war, conflict, and the underworld.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In one stele he is portrayed with a rope tied around his neck, and in another with an incense bag, together signifying a sacrifice to end a cycle of years.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Based on observations of modern Maya rituals, Gronemeyer and MacLeod claim that the stela refers to a celebration in which a person portraying Bolon Yokteʼ Kʼuh was wrapped in ceremonial garments and paraded around the site.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] They note that the association of Bolon Yokteʼ Kʼuh with bʼakʼtun 13 appears to be so important on this inscription that it supersedes more typical celebrations such as "erection of stelae, scattering of incense" and so forth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Furthermore, they assert that this event was indeed planned for 2012 and not the 7th century.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Mayanist scholar Stephen Houston contests this view by arguing that future dates on Maya inscriptions were simply meant to draw parallels with contemporary events, and that the words on the stela describe a contemporary rather than a future scene.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In April–May 2012, a team of archaeologists unearthed a previously unknown inscription on a stairway at the La Corona site in Guatemala.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The inscription, on what is known as Hieroglyphic Stairway 12, describes the establishment of a royal court in Calakmul in 635 AD, and compares the then-recent completion of 13 kʼatuns with the future completion of the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] It contains no speculation or prophecy as to what the scribes believed would happen at that time.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Maya inscriptions occasionally mention predicted future events or commemorations that would occur on dates far beyond the completion of the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Most of these are in the form of "distance dates"; Long Count dates together with an additional number, known as a Distance Number, which when added to them makes a future date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On the west panel at the Temple of Inscriptions in Palenque, a section of text projects forward to the 80th 52-year Calendar Round from the coronation of the ruler Kʼinich Janaabʼ Pakal.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Pakal's accession occurred on 9.9.2.4.8, equivalent to 27 July 615 AD in the proleptic Gregorian calendar.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The inscription begins with Pakal's birthdate of 9.8.9.13.0 (24 March, 603 AD Gregorian) and then adds the Distance Number 10.11.10.5.8 to it, arriving at a date of 21 October 4772 AD, more than 4,000 years after Pakal's time.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] According to Linda Schele, these 13s represent "the starting point of a huge odometer of time", with each acting as a zero and resetting to 1 as the numbers increase.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Thus this inscription anticipates the current universe lasting at least 2021×13×360 days, or roughly 2.687×1028 years; a time span equal to 2 quintillion times the age of the universe as determined by cosmologists.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Others have suggested that this date marks creation as having occurred after that time span.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, researchers announced the discovery of a series of Maya astronomical tables in Xultún, Guatemala which plot the movements of the Moon and other astronomical bodies over the course of 17 bʼakʼtuns.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Many assertions about the year 2012 form part of Mayanism, a non-codified collection of New Age beliefs about ancient Maya wisdom and spirituality.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The term is distinct from "Mayanist," used to refer to an academic scholar of the Maya.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Archaeoastronomer Anthony Aveni says that while the idea of "balancing the cosmos" was prominent in ancient Maya literature, the 2012 phenomenon did not draw from those traditions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Instead, it was bound up with American concepts such as the New Age movement, 2012 millenarianism, and the belief in secret knowledge from distant times and places.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Themes found in 2012 literature included "suspicion towards mainstream Western culture", the idea of spiritual evolution, and the possibility of leading the world into the New Age by individual example or by a group's joined consciousness.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The general intent of this literature was not to warn of impending doom but "to foster counter-cultural sympathies and eventually socio-political and 'spiritual' activism".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 1975, the ending of bʼakʼtun 13 became the subject of speculation by several New Age authors, who asserted it would correspond with a global "transformation of consciousness".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Some research suggests that both Argüelles and McKenna were heavily influenced in this regard by the Mayanism of American author William S.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Burroughs, who first portrayed the end of the Mayan Long Count as an apocalyptic shift of human consciousness in 1960's *The Exterminator*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 1983, with the publication of Robert J.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Sharer's revised table of date correlations in the 4th edition of Morley's *The Ancient Maya,* each became convinced that 21 December 2012 had significant meaning.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] By 1987, the year in which he organized the Harmonic Convergence event, Argüelles was using the date 21 December 2012 in *The Mayan Factor: Path Beyond Technology*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] He believed that the Maya aligned their calendar to correspond to this phenomenon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Anthony Aveni has dismissed all of these ideas.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2001, Robert Bast wrote the first online articles regarding the possibility of a doomsday in 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2006, author Daniel Pinchbeck popularized New Age concepts about this date in his book *2012: The Return of Quetzalcoatl*, linking bʼakʼtun 13 to beliefs in crop circles, alien abduction, and personal revelations based on the use of hallucinogenic drugs and mediumship.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Pinchbeck claims to discern a "growing realization that materialism and the rational, empirical worldview that comes with it has reached its expiration date ... [w]e're on the verge of transitioning to a dispensation of consciousness that's more intuitive, mystical and shamanic".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] There is no significant astronomical event tied to the Long Count's start date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Its supposed end date was tied to astronomical phenomena by esoteric, fringe, and New Age literature that placed great significance on astrology, especially astrological interpretations associated with the phenomenon of axial precession.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Chief among these ideas is the astrological concept of a "galactic alignment".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In the Solar System, the planets and the Sun lie roughly within the same flat plane, known as the plane of the ecliptic.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] From our perspective on Earth, the ecliptic is the path taken by the Sun across the sky over the course of the year.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The twelve constellations that line the ecliptic are known as the zodiacal constellations, and, annually, the Sun passes through all of them in turn.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Additionally, over time, the Sun's annual cycle appears to recede very slowly backward by one degree every 72 years, or by one constellation approximately every 2,160 years.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This backward movement, called "precession", is due to a slight wobble in the Earth's axis as it spins, and can be compared to the way a spinning top wobbles as it slows down.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Over the course of 25,800 years, a period often called a Great Year, the Sun's path completes a full, 360-degree backward rotation through the zodiac.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In Western astrological traditions, precession is measured from the March equinox, one of the two annual points at which the Sun is exactly halfway between its lowest and highest points in the sky.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] At the end of the 20th century and beginning of the 21st, the Sun's March equinox position was in the constellation Pisces moving back into Aquarius.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This signaled the end of one astrological age (the Age of Pisces) and the beginning of another (the Age of Aquarius).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Similarly, the Sun's December solstice position (in the northern hemisphere, the lowest point on its annual path; in the southern hemisphere, the highest) was in the constellation of Sagittarius, one of two constellations in which the zodiac intersects with the Milky Way.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Every year, on the December solstice, the Sun and the Milky Way, appear (from the surface of the Earth) to come into alignment, and every year precession caused a slight shift in the Sun's position in the Milky Way.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Given that the Milky Way is between 10° and 20° wide, it takes between 700 and 1,400 years for the Sun's December solstice position to precess through it.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2012 it was about halfway through the Milky Way, crossing the galactic equator.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the Sun's December solstice fell on 21 December.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Mystical speculations about the precession of the equinoxes and the Sun's proximity to the center of the Milky Way appeared in *Hamlet's Mill* (1969) by Giorgio de Santillana and Hertha von Deschend.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] These were quoted and expanded upon by Terence and Dennis McKenna in *The Invisible Landscape* (1975).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Adherents to the idea, following a theory first proposed by Munro Edmonson, alleged that the Maya based their calendar on observations of the Great Rift or Dark Rift, a band of dark dust clouds in the Milky Way, which, according to some scholars, the Maya called the *Xibalba be* or "Black Road".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] John Major Jenkins claims that the Maya were aware of where the ecliptic intersected the Black Road and gave this position in the sky a special significance in their cosmology.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins said that precession would align the Sun precisely with the galactic equator at the 2012 winter solstice.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins claimed that the classical Maya anticipated this conjunction and celebrated it as the harbinger of a profound spiritual transition for mankind.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] New Age proponents of the galactic alignment hypothesis argued that, just as astrology uses the positions of stars and planets to make claims of future events, the Maya plotted their calendars with the objective of preparing for significant world events.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins attributed the insights of ancient Maya shamans about the Galactic Center to their use of psilocybin mushrooms, psychoactive toads, and other psychedelics.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins also associated the *Xibalba be* with a "world tree", drawing on studies of contemporary (not ancient) Maya cosmology.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers such as David Morrison argue that the galactic equator is an entirely arbitrary line and can never be precisely drawn, because it is impossible to determine the Milky Way's exact boundaries, which vary depending on clarity of view.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins claimed he drew his conclusions about the location of the galactic equator from observations taken at above 11,000 feet (3,400 m), an altitude that gives a clearer image of the Milky Way than the Maya had access to.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Furthermore, since the Sun is half a degree wide, its solstice position takes 36 years to precess its full width.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins himself noted that even given his determined location for the line of the galactic equator, its most precise convergence with the center of the Sun already occurred in 1998, and so asserts that, rather than 2012, the galactic alignment instead focuses on a multi-year period centered in 1998.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] There is no clear evidence that the classic Maya were aware of precession.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Some Maya scholars, such as Barbara MacLeod, Michael Grofe, Eva Hunt, Gordon Brotherston, and Anthony Aveni, have suggested that some Mayan holy dates were timed to precessional cycles, but scholarly opinion on the subject remains divided.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] There is also little evidence, archaeological or historical, that the Maya placed any importance on solstices or equinoxes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] It is possible that only the earliest among Mesoamericans observed solstices, but this is also a disputed issue among Mayanists.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] There is also no evidence that the classic Maya attached any importance to the Milky Way; there is no glyph in their writing system to represent it, and no astronomical or chronological table tied to it.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] "Timewave zero" is a numerological formula that purports to calculate the ebb and flow of "novelty", defined as increase over time in the universe's interconnectedness, or organized complexity.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Terence McKenna claimed that the universe has a teleological attractor at the end of time that increases interconnectedness.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] He believed this which would eventually reach a singularity of infinite complexity in 2012, at which point anything and everything imaginable would occur simultaneously.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] He conceived this idea over several years in the early to mid-1970s whilst using psilocybin mushrooms and DMT.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The scientific community considers novelty theory to be pseudoscience.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] McKenna expressed "novelty" in a computer program which produces a waveform known as "timewave zero" or the "timewave".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Based on McKenna's interpretation of the King Wen sequence of the *I Ching*, an ancient Chinese book on divination, the graph purports to show great periods of novelty corresponding with major shifts in humanity's biological and sociocultural evolution.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] He believed that the events of any given time are resonantly related to the events of other times, and chose the atomic bombing of Hiroshima as the basis for calculating his end date of November 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] When he later discovered this date's proximity to the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun of the Maya calendar, he revised his hypothesis so that the two dates matched.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The 1975 first edition of *The Invisible Landscape* referred to 2012 (but no specific day during the year) only twice.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In the 1993 second edition, McKenna employed Sharer's date of 21 December 2012 throughout.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The idea that the year 2012 presaged a world cataclysm, the end of the world, or the end of human civilization, became a subject of popular media speculation as the date of 21 December 2012 approached.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This idea was promulgated by many pages on the Internet, particularly on YouTube.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Discovery Channel was criticized for its "quasi-documentaries" about the subject that "sacrifice[d] accuracy for entertainment".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Some people interpreted the galactic alignment apocalyptically, claiming that its occurrence would somehow create a combined gravitational effect between the Sun and the supermassive black hole at the center of our galaxy (known as Sagittarius A*), creating havoc on Earth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Apart from the "galactic alignment" already having happened in 1998, the Sun's apparent path through the zodiac as seen from Earth did not take it near the true galactic center, but rather several degrees above it.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Even were this not the case, Sagittarius A* is 30,000 light years from Earth; it would have to have been more than 6 million times closer to cause any gravitational disruption to Earth's Solar System.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This reading of the alignment was included on the History Channel documentary *Decoding the Past*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] John Major Jenkins complained that a science fiction writer co-authored the documentary, and he went on to characterize it as "45 minutes of unabashed doomsday hype and the worst kind of inane sensationalism".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Some believers in a 2012 doomsday used the term "galactic alignment" to describe a different phenomenon proposed by some scientists to explain a pattern in mass extinctions supposedly observed in the fossil record.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] According to the Shiva hypothesis, mass extinctions are not random, but recur every 26 million years.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] To account for this, it was suggested that vertical oscillations made by the Sun on its 250-million-year orbit of the galactic center cause it to regularly pass through the galactic plane.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] When the Sun's orbit takes it outside the galactic plane which bisects the galactic disc, the influence of the galactic tide is weaker.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This "alignment" takes place over tens of millions of years, and could never be timed to an exact date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Evidence shows that the Sun passed through the plane bisecting the galactic disc three million years ago and in 2012 was moving farther above it.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] A third suggested alignment was some sort of planetary conjunction occurring on 21 December 2012; there was no conjunction on that date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Multi-planet alignments did occur in both 2000 and 2010, each with no ill result for the Earth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jupiter is the largest planet in the Solar System, being larger than all other planets combined.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] When Jupiter is near opposition, the difference in gravitational force that the Earth experiences is less than 1% of the force that the Earth feels daily from the Moon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Another idea tied to 2012 involved a geomagnetic reversal (often referred to as a pole shift by proponents), possibly triggered by a massive solar flare, that would release an energy equal to 100 billion atomic bombs.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This belief was supposedly supported by observations that the Earth's magnetic field was weakening, which could precede a reversal of the north and south magnetic poles, and the arrival of the next solar maximum, which was expected sometime around 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Most scientific estimates say that geomagnetic reversals take between 1,000 and 10,000 years to complete, and do not start on any particular date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration predicted that the solar maximum would peak in late 2013 or 2014, and that it would be fairly weak, with a below-average number of sunspots.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] There was no scientific evidence linking a solar maximum to a geomagnetic reversal, which is driven by forces entirely within the Earth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] A solar maximum does affect satellite and cellular phone communications.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On 23 July 2012, a massive, potentially damaging, solar storm came within nine days of striking Earth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Some believers in a 2012 doomsday claimed that a planet called Planet X, or Nibiru, would collide with or pass by the Earth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This idea, which had appeared in various forms since 1995, initially predicted Doomsday in May 2003, but proponents abandoned that date after it passed without incident.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The idea originated from claims of channeling alien beings and is widely ridiculed.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers calculated that such an object so close to Earth would be visible to anyone looking up at the night sky.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Author Graham Hancock, in his book *Fingerprints of the Gods*, interpreted Coe's remarks in *Breaking the Maya Code* as evidence for the prophecy of a global cataclysm.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Filmmaker Roland Emmerich later credited the book with inspiring his 2009 disaster film *2012*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Other speculations regarding doomsday in 2012 included predictions by the Web Bot project, a computer program that purports to predict the future by analyzing Internet chatter.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Commentators have rejected claims that the bot is able to predict natural disasters, as opposed to human-caused disasters like stock market crashes.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The 2012 date was also loosely tied to the long-running concept of the **photon belt**, which predicted a form of interaction between Earth and Alcyone, the largest star of the Pleiades cluster.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Critics argued that photons cannot form belts, that the Pleiades, located more than 400 light years away, could have no effect on Earth, and that the Solar System, rather than getting closer to the Pleiades, was in fact moving farther away from it.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Some media outlets tied the fact that the red supergiant star Betelgeuse would undergo a supernova at some point in the future to the 2012 phenomenon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] While Betelgeuse was certainly in the final stages of its life, and would die as a supernova, there was no way to predict the timing of the event to within 100,000 years.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] To be a threat to Earth, a supernova would need to be no further than 25 light years from the Solar System.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Betelgeuse is roughly 600 light years away, and so its supernova would not affect Earth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In December 2011, NASA's Francis Reddy issued a press release debunking the possibility of a supernova occurring in 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In December 2010, an article, first published in examiner.com and later referenced in the English-language edition of *Pravda* claimed, citing a Second Digitized Sky Survey photograph as evidence, that SETI had detected three large spacecraft due to arrive at Earth in 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Astronomer and debunker Phil Plait noted that by using the small-angle formula, one could determine that if the object in the photo were as large as claimed, it would have had to be closer to Earth than the Moon, which would mean it would already have arrived.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In January 2011, Seth Shostak, chief astronomer of SETI, issued a press release debunking the claims.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon spread widely after coming to public notice, particularly on the Internet, and hundreds of thousands of websites made reference to it.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] "Ask an Astrobiologist", a NASA public outreach website, received over 5,000 questions from the public on the subject from 2007, some asking whether they should kill themselves, their children or their pets.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] At least one suicide was directly linked to fear of a 2012 apocalypse, with others anecdotally reported.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jared Lee Loughner, the perpetrator of the 2011 Tucson shooting, followed 2012-related predictions.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] A panel of scientists questioned on the topic at a plenary session at the Astronomical Society of the Pacific contended that the Internet played a substantial role in allowing this doomsday date to gain more traction than previous similar panics.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Beginning in 2000, the small French village of Bugarach, population 189, began receiving visits from "esoterics"—mystic believers who had concluded that the local mountain, Pic de Bugarach, was the ideal location to weather the transformative events of 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2011, the local mayor, Jean-Pierre Delord, began voicing fears to the international press that the small town would be overwhelmed by an influx of thousands of visitors in 2012, even suggesting he might call in the army.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] "We've seen a huge rise in visitors", Delord told *The Independent* in March 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] "Already this year more than 20,000 people have climbed right to the top, and last year we had 10,000 hikers, which was a significant rise on the previous 12 months.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] They think Pic de Bugarach is 'un garage à ovnis' [a garage for UFOs].
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The villagers are exasperated: the exaggerated importance of something which they see as completely removed from reality is bewildering.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] After 21 December, this will surely return to normal." In December 2012, the French government placed 100 police and firefighters around both Bugarach and Pic de Bugarach, limiting access to potential visitors.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Ultimately, only about 1,000 visitors appeared at the height of the "event".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Two raves were foiled, 12 people had to be turned away from the peak, and 5 people were arrested for carrying weapons.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jean-Pierre Delord was criticised by members of the community for failing to take advantage of the media attention and promote the region.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Turkish village of Şirince, near Ephesus, expected to receive over 60,000 visitors on 21 December 2012, as New Age mystics believed its "positive energy" would aid in weathering the catastrophe.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Only a fraction of that number actually arrived, with a substantial component being police and journalists, and the expected windfall failed to materialise.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Similarly, the pyramid-like mountain of Rtanj, in the Serbian Carpathians, attracted attention, due to rumors that it would emit a powerful force shield on the day, protecting those in the vicinity.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In Russia, inmates of a women's prison experienced "a collective mass psychosis" in the weeks leading up to the supposed doomsday, while residents of a factory town near Moscow reportedly emptied a supermarket of matches, candles, food and other supplies.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Minister of Emergency Situations declared in response that according to "methods of monitoring what is occurring on the planet Earth", there would be no apocalypse in December.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In December 2012, Vatican astronomer Rev.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] José Funes wrote in the Vatican newspaper *L'Osservatore Romano* that apocalyptic theories around 2012 were "not even worth discussing".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In May 2011, 5,000-7,000 Hmong ethnic people in Dien Bien province, Vietnam held a protest on the grounds that the end of the world was coming, and the Hmong people would be evacuated to their own Hmong country by "supernatural force".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Vietnamese media and government believe that this is a trick of the Hmong ethnic separatist forces.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In China, up to a thousand members of the Christian cult Almighty God were arrested after claiming that the end of bʼakʼtun 13 marked the end of the world, and that it was time to overthrow Communism.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Shoppers were reported to be hoarding supplies of candles in anticipation of coming darkness, while online retailer Taobao sold tickets to board Noah's Ark to customers.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Bookings for wedding ceremonies on 21 December 2012 were saturated in several cities.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On 14 December 2012, a man in Henan province attacked and wounded twenty-three children with a knife.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Authorities suspected the man had been "influenced" by the prediction of the upcoming apocalypse.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Academics in China attributed the widespread belief in the 2012 doomsday in their country to a lack of scientific literacy and a mistrust of the government-controlled media.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On 6 December 2012, Australian Prime Minister Julia Gillard delivered a hoax speech for the radio station triple J in which she declared "My dear remaining fellow Australians; the end of the world is coming.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Jasper Tsang, president of Hong Kong's Legislative Council, adjourned the legislature's sitting on 20 December 2012 by announcing that he "would not permit the world to end" as the legislature had to meet again in January 2013, to the laughter of MPs.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Mesoamerican countries that once formed part of the Maya civilization—Mexico, Belize, Guatemala, Honduras, and El Salvador—all organized festivities to commemorate the end of bʼakʼtun 13 at the largest Maya sites.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2011, the Maya town of Tapachula in Chiapas activated an eight-foot digital clock counting down the days until the end of bʼakʼtun 13.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2012, major events took place at Chichén Itzá in Mexico and Tikal in Guatemala.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In El Salvador, the largest event was held at Tazumal, and in Honduras, at Copán.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In all of these archaeological sites, Maya rituals were held at dawn led by shamans and Maya priests.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On the final day of bʼakʼtun 13, residents of Yucatán and other regions formerly dominated by the ancient Maya celebrated what they saw as the dawn of a new, better era.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] According to official figures from Mexico's National Institute of Anthropology and History (INAH), about 50,000 people visited Mexican archaeological sites on 21 December 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Of those, 10,000 visited Chichén Itzá in Yucatán, 9,900 visited Tulum in Quintana Roo, and 8,000 visited Palenque in Chiapas.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] An additional 10,000 people visited Teotihuacan near Mexico City, which is not a Maya site.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The main ceremony in Chichén Itzá was held at dawn in the plaza of the Temple of Kukulkán, one of the principal symbols of Maya culture.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The archaeological site was opened two hours early to receive thousands of tourists, mostly foreigners who came to participate in events scheduled for the end of bʼakʼtun 13.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The fire ceremony at Tikal was held at dawn in the main plaza of the Temple of the Great Jaguar.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The ceremony was led by Guatemalan and foreign priests.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The President of Guatemala, Otto Pérez, and of Costa Rica, Laura Chinchilla, participated in the event as special guests.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] During the ceremony the priests asked for unity, peace and the end of discrimination and racism, with the hope that the start of a new cycle will be a "new dawn".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] About 3,000 people participated in the event.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Most of these events were organized by agencies of the Mexican and Central American governments, and their respective tourism industries expected to attract thousands of visitors.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Mexico is visited by about 22 million foreigners in a typical year.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the national tourism agency expected to attract 52 million visitors just to the regions of Chiapas, Yucatán, Quintana Roo, Tabasco and Campeche.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] A Maya activist group in Guatemala, Oxlaljuj Ajpop, objected to the commercialization of the date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] A spokesman from the Conference of Maya Ministers commented that for them the Tikal ceremony is not a show for tourists but something spiritual and personal.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The secretary of the Great Council of Ancestral Authorities commented that living Maya felt they were excluded from the activities in Tikal.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] This group held a parallel ceremony, and complained that the date has been used for commercial gain.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In addition, before the main Tikal ceremony, about 200 Maya protested the celebration because they felt excluded.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Most modern Maya were indifferent to the ceremonies, and the small number of people still practising ancient rites held solemn, more private ceremonies.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Osvaldo Gomez, a technical advisor to the Tikal site, complained that many visitors during the celebration had illegally climbed the stairs of the Temple of the Masks, causing "irreparable" damage.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In Brazil, Décio Colla, the Mayor of the City of São Francisco de Paula, Rio Grande do Sul, mobilized the population to prepare for the end of the world by stocking up on food and supplies.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In the city of Corguinho, in the Mato Grosso do Sul, a colony was built for survivors of the expected tragedy.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In Alto Paraíso de Goiás, the hotels also made specific reservations for prophetic dates.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In Bolivia, President Evo Morales participated in Quechua and Aymara rituals, organized with government support, to commemorate the Southern solstice that took place in Isla del Sol, in the southern part of Lake Titicaca.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] During the event, Morales proclaimed the beginning of "*Pachakuti*", meaning the world's wake up to a culture of life and the beginning of the end to world capitalism, and he proposed to dismantle the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2012, the Uritorco mountain in Córdoba, Argentina was closed, as a mass suicide there had been proposed on Facebook.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In the United States, sales of private underground blast shelters increased noticeably after 2009, with many construction companies' advertisements calling attention to the 2012 apocalypse.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In Michigan, schools were closed for the Christmas holidays two days early, in part because rumours of the 2012 apocalypse were raising fears of repeat shootings similar to that at Sandy Hook.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] American reality TV stars Heidi Montag and Spencer Pratt revealed that they had spent most of their $10 million of accumulated earnings by 2010 because they believed the world would end in 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The 2012 phenomenon was discussed or referenced by several media outlets.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Several TV documentaries, as well as some contemporary fictional references to the year 2012, referred to 21 December as the day of a cataclysmic event.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The TV series *The X-Files* cited 22 December 2012 as the date for an alien colonization of the Earth, and mentioned the Mayan calendar "stopping" on this date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The History Channel aired a handful of special series on doomsday that included analysis of 2012 theories, such as *Decoding the Past* (2005–2007), *2012, End of Days* (2006), *Last Days on Earth* (2006), *Seven Signs of the Apocalypse* (2009), and *Nostradamus 2012* (2008).
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The Discovery Channel also aired *2012 Apocalypse* in 2009, suggesting that massive solar storms, magnetic pole reversal, earthquakes, supervolcanoes, and other drastic natural events could occur in 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the National Geographic Channel launched a show called *Doomsday Preppers*, a documentary series about survivalists preparing for various cataclysms, including the 2012 doomsday.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Hundreds of books were published on the topic.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The bestselling book of 2009, Dan Brown's *The Lost Symbol*, featured a coded mock email number (2456282.5) that decoded to the Julian date for 21 December 2012.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In the Ubisoft game franchise *Assassin's Creed*, the overarching plotline of the games starring the first protagonist, Desmond Miles, was also inspired by the phenomenon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] After escaping capture by the Knights Templar, Desmond rejoins the Assassins Brotherhood to help them fight the Templars and prevent the predicted end of the world, in this case caused by a cyclical solar flare.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] As these promotions did not mention the film itself, many viewers believed them to be real and contacted astronomers in panic.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Although the campaign was criticized, the film became one of the most successful of its year, grossing nearly $770 million worldwide.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] An article in *The Daily Telegraph* attributed the widespread fear of the phenomenon in China to the film, which was a hit in the country as it depicted the Chinese building "survival arks".
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Lars von Trier's 2011 film *Melancholia* featured a plot in which a planet emerges from behind the Sun on a collision course with Earth.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon also inspired several rock and pop music hits.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] As early as 1997, "A Certain Shade of Green" by Incubus referred to the mystical belief that a shift in perception would arrive in 2012 ("Are you gonna stand around till 2012 A.D.? / What are you waiting for, a certain shade of green?").
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Towards mid-December 2012, an internet hoax related to South Korean singer Psy being one of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse was widely circulated around social media platforms.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The hoax purported that once Psy's "Gangnam Style" YouTube video amassed a billion views, the world would end.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] Rahman, known for *Slumdog Millionaire*, released his single "Infinite Love" to "instill faith and optimism in people" prior to the hypothesized doomsday.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The artwork for All Time Low's 2012 album *Don't Panic* satirizes various cataclysmic events associated with the phenomenon.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon was also satirized in Brian M.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] A number of brands ran commercials tied to the phenomenon in the days and months leading to the date.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] In February 2012, American automotive company General Motors aired an advertisement during the annual Super Bowl football game in which a group of friends drove Chevrolet Silverados through the ruins of human civilization following the 2012 apocalypse.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] On 17 December 2012, Jell-O ran an ad saying that offering Jell-O to the Mayan gods would appease them into sparing the world.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/2012-phenomenon] John Verret, Professor of Advertising at Boston University, questioned the utility of tying large sums of money to such a unique and short-term event.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] This conspiracy theory has been debunked in several ways.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] The *Orkney* supposedly sank in the Baltic Sea, en route from London to St.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] Petersburg, then the capital of the Russian Empire.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] Alexander Keith, who was known by several aliases, including William Thompson, had experience previously exploding ships to claim insurance money in Europe.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] His most well-known was that of the *Mosel* which occurred later.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] It has also been suggested that Keith may have been involved in the sinking of at least two other ships - the SS *City of Boston* and the *Marie Victoria*.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] In 2014, Russian politician, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, of the Liberal Democratic Party of Russia has brought up these claims, as well as the bribery related to the deal.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] There are several pieces of evidence that contradict this conspiracy theory.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] As a start, the money was used to buy railroad equipment that was intended for Kursk-Kiev, Ryazan, Kozlovsky, Moscow-Ryazan and other railway lines.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] This suggests the funds were spent immediately, suggesting that it would not be possible for it to have been sent in gold.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] Secondly, according to the conspiracy theory, the *Orkney* exploded before the money was due.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] It is claimed that the ship was sunk in mid-July 1868, while the payment was supposed to be delivered on 1 August 1868.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] Furthermore, there is no record of a ship called the *Orkney* going missing, only a similarly named ship called *Orkney Lass*, which was registered after the events as still in operation and was supposedly travelling to South America that year, not St.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] No gold has ever been found in the Baltic Sea.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] Lastly, bombs were very complicated to make at the time and Keith Jr. would spend a lot of time to prepare one.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] There are also conflicting stories about how Keith became involved—one story claims he was approached while living in Germany, the other says he thought of the scheme while working as a stevedore in England.
[src:alaska-payment-conspiracy/alaska-payment-conspiracy] Finally, there is a lack of evidence to connect Keith to the bombing, only that he was involved in the *Mosel* bombing a decade later.
